            <header>
              <h2 class="h1">How King Penguins Regulate Their Temperature</h2>
            </header>
            <p>King penguins (<i>Aptenodytes patagonicus</i>) live in extreme environments. On land, they experience temperatures below -20ËšC. Here, they maintain surprisingly high core temperatures (~37 degrees Celsius). At sea, staying warm is even more challenging, because water cools the penguins down faster than air. This because air has a lower <i>thermal conductivity</i> than water.</p>
            <p>From these insights, we know that king penguins are the coldest, or most <i>thermally stressed</i>, when they are in the water fishing. How can they survive these harsh temperatures? Many sea mammals stay warm with thick fur or fat on their body. King penguins have both layers of fat and a dense coat of feathers. However, their fins and feet are more exposed. Their feet are naked, and their flippers have only short feathers. King penguins are adapted to let their flippers and feet -- their <i>appendages</i> -- remain colder than their main body -- their <i>core</i>. They massively reduce the amount of blood going in and out of their appendages, a process called <i>vasoconstriction</i>. This reduces heat exchange between the appendages and their core body. This way, a penguin's cold feet and flippers don't send much cold blood back to their core body, which would cool down their core temperature. King penguin veins are also structured so the warm blood from their heart passes by the cold blood from their appendages to warm it up, reducing even further the cold blood coming into their core body. This is called <i>counter-current heat exchange</i>. Both adaptations can reduce heat loss to 2-6% of total heat loss compared to 19-48%.</p>
            <br>
            <p>Q1: What is more important: appendage temperature or core body temperature? Why?</p>
            <p>Q2: Reflect on why these adaptations are important for king penguins in their habitat.</p>
            <br>
            <p><img src="/images/king-penguins-hypothermic.jpg" style="width:50%; margin-top:75px"></p>
            <p>Hypothermia occurs when your internal temperature is too cold. King penguins, depending on how long they stay in cold waters, can become partially or fully hypothermic. A penguin is only partially hypothermic if only its appendages are at a low temperature, but its core body is at a normal temperature. A penguin is fully hypothermic if its core body temperature is also low.</p>
            <br>
            <p>Q3: Why are penguin feet and flippers not more insulated to keep them warmer?</p>
            <br>
            <p>While it is important, especially in the Antarctic, for penguins to stay warm, it is also important for penguins not to overheat. When king penguins are on land for a long time and are being active, there is a possibility of overheating. This is why a penguin's feet are naked and their flippers have shorter feathers. Areas of an animal's body that are less insulated and allow them to cool off are called <i>thermal windows</i>. Little heat escapes from a penguin's core body, but they can cool down using their flippers and feet. By exposing more of their flippers, king penguins can finely control their internal body temperature.</p>
            <br>
            <p>Q4: How are king penguins able to control their core body temperature using their feet?</p>

            <p><img src="/images/king-penguins-thermoregulation.jpg" style="width:50%; margin-top:75px"></p>
            <p>Q5: Noting the differences in position between the thermal windows (flippers and feet) of these two penguins, which penguin is warming up and which penguin is cooling down? What informs your decision?</p>
