            <p>Along with their thick feathers, emperor penguins use huddling to warm themselves up. By pressing together, they reduce how much radiative cooling happens. They also block themselves from wind. Some penguins are on the outside of the huddle, which means they take the brunt of the wind. Luckily, the huddle swirls, like a tornado, and the one who are on the outside of the huddle get brought inside, so they can warm up too. From sharing body heat, the center of a penguin huddle can reach temperatures of up to 37 degrees Celsius!</p>
